poem:
The Sciencefair Wight

Twas labblig at the fairgrounds, and the glintly projects hummed,
The fizzlenoggers fumbled, and the whifflesticks were plumbed;
Beware the Sparkwick, my child! the Glowerproof! the Judge-snarl grim!
Hold fast thy flibberflask and wit, and mind thy bright-eyed prim.

He took his solder-sword in hand; long time the gizmo-glow he eyed —
And stood awhile by poster-board where tiny theories bide;
And as the ticking tomes did tick and test-tubes glorp and sing,
Came wobble-wires and bumbling blots that tried to steal his spring.

One, two! One, two! And through they flew, the fizz and foobar throng;
He switched the flux and tuned the hum, he spoke his data song;
The Sparkwhiff hissed, the Volt-gnash snapped — but lo! his circuit true,
Unfurled the light, the model sang, the judges hummed, “A clue!”

O Callooh! Callay! they cried — Hoorah! the ribbon bright he bore;
Back through the whirligiggy lanes he tramped to home's warm door;
So heed, young chums, before you go: prepare thy plots and proofs,
And brave the fair with curious heart — return with tinkered truths.
